AP Pay Equity

1/4/2020

Rendered at 11:59 AM, Jan. 08, 2020

Overview

This is a study of pay equity for guild-covered employees across factors such as gender, age and race/ethnicity.

Only “Class A” employees working 30 hours or more a week are considered in the study.

The overall findings:

  • Broadly speaking, there exists a slight disparity in pay between men and women at the AP.

  • When looking at other factors such as race/ethnicity and age, this disparity grows larger but also more nuanced.

  • There can be much more disparity within specific desks or in specific bureaus than at the company as a whole.

The limitations of the study:

  • Age and time working at the company were used as proxies for experience in journalism.

  • The study used the company’s classifications for working units and areas. This may not line up with existing realities of who works with whom, or what the distribution of responsibilities may be.

  • For some demographic categories, there is not enough representation to speak confidently to disparity that may or may not exist.

Future goals:

  • The study could be improved with a better understanding of the different desks and which employees are doing equivalent work

Gender

The study covered 685 employees. Looking at salary before taking into account any other factors:

The median being smaller than the mean in all cases indicates that the salary distribution for all genders is skewed such that a small proportion of higher salaries has pushed the overall average up.

Age and experience

We do not have data on how many years of experience an employee has overall in journalism, but the data does include the age of an employee, which we will use as a proxy for experience.

After including age, it appears like pay disparity between genders reverses based on age: for younger employees, men are paid slightly more, while among employees over 50 the balance shifts the other way where women are paid slightly more.

Areas

Splitting the company into two groups by area - those with the cost of living differential and those without. While the differential itself represents a pay increase on its own, we can additionally study whether employees who work outside the cities that receive the differential see worse pay equity.

There are only 8 offices with 5 or more women, representing 383 employees total or 55.9% of employees.
